Table: Buses

+--------------+------+
| Column Name  | Type |
+--------------+------+
| bus_id       | int  |
| arrival_time | int  |
| capacity     | int  |
+--------------+------+
bus_id contains unique values.
Each row of this table contains information about the arrival time of a bus at the LeetCode station and its capacity (the number of empty seats it has).
No two buses will arrive at the same time and all bus capacities will be positive integers.
 

Table: Passengers

+--------------+------+
| Column Name  | Type |
+--------------+------+
| passenger_id | int  |
| arrival_time | int  |
+--------------+------+
passenger_id contains unique values.
Each row of this table contains information about the arrival time of a passenger at the LeetCode station.
 

Buses and passengers arrive at the LeetCode station. If a bus arrives at the station at a time tbus and a passenger arrived at a time tpassenger where tpassenger <= tbus and the passenger did not catch any bus, the passenger will use that bus. In addition, each bus has a capacity. If at the moment the bus arrives at the station there are more passengers waiting than its capacity capacity, only capacity passengers will use the bus.

Write a solution to report the number of users that used each bus.

Return the result table ordered by bus_id in ascending order.

The result format is in the following example.

 

Example 1:

Input: 
Buses table:
+--------+--------------+----------+
| bus_id | arrival_time | capacity |
+--------+--------------+----------+
| 1      | 2            | 1        |
| 2      | 4            | 10       |
| 3      | 7            | 2        |
+--------+--------------+----------+
Passengers table:
+--------------+--------------+
| passenger_id | arrival_time |
+--------------+--------------+
| 11           | 1            |
| 12           | 1            |
| 13           | 5            |
| 14           | 6            |
| 15           | 7            |
+--------------+--------------+
Output: 
+--------+----------------+
| bus_id | passengers_cnt |
+--------+----------------+
| 1      | 1              |
| 2      | 1              |
| 3      | 2              |
+--------+----------------+
Explanation: 
- Passenger 11 arrives at time 1.
- Passenger 12 arrives at time 1.
- Bus 1 arrives at time 2 and collects passenger 11 as it has one empty seat.

- Bus 2 arrives at time 4 and collects passenger 12 as it has ten empty seats.

- Passenger 12 arrives at time 5.
- Passenger 13 arrives at time 6.
- Passenger 14 arrives at time 7.
- Bus 3 arrives at time 7 and collects passengers 12 and 13 as it has two empty seats.
 


SOLUTION
with recursive cte as(
    select 0 as t
),
eligible as 
(
    select  ROW_NUMBER() OVER(ORDER BY arrival_time) as rnk,bus_id , capacity,count(passenger_id) as eligible_passenger  from 
    (
    select a.bus_id,a.capacity,b.passenger_id ,a.arrival_time
    from Buses as a 
    left JOIN 
    Passengers as b 
    on a.arrival_time>=b.arrival_time
    )s 
    group by bus_id
),
onboarded as 
(
    select rnk,bus_id,capacity,eligible_passenger,
    case when capacity <=eligible_passenger then capacity else eligible_passenger end as onboarded_passenger,
    case when capacity <=eligible_passenger then capacity else eligible_passenger end as total_onboarded
    from eligible where rnk=1
    union all 
    select a.rnk,a.bus_id,a.capacity,
    a.eligible_passenger-b.total_onboarded as eligible_passenger,
    case when a.capacity <=(a.eligible_passenger-b.total_onboarded) then a.capacity else (a.eligible_passenger-b.total_onboarded) end  as onboarded_passenger  ,
    b.total_onboarded+ (case when a.capacity <=(a.eligible_passenger-b.total_onboarded) then a.capacity else (a.eligible_passenger-b.total_onboarded) end ) as total_onboarded
    from eligible as a 
    JOIN 
    onboarded as b 
    on a.rnk-1=b.rnk
)
select bus_id,onboarded_passenger as passengers_cnt  from onboarded
order by bus_id


THOUGHT PROCESS
Core Idea

For every bus:

Find all passengers who arrived before or at the bus arrival time.
Among them, only some can board because:
Previous buses may already have taken passengers.
The current bus has limited capacity.

So we need to:

Track eligible passengers
Track already onboarded passengers
Reduce remaining eligible passengers for upcoming buses
Step 1 — Find Eligible Passengers

A passenger is eligible for a bus if:

passenger.arrival_time≤bus.arrival_time

We first create a CTE joining buses and passengers.

WITH cte AS (
    SELECT
        b.*,
        p.passenger_id,
        p.arrival_time AS passenger_arrival
    FROM buses b
    JOIN passengers p
        ON p.arrival_time <= b.arrival_time
)

This gives all possible eligible passengers for every bus.

Step 2 — Count Eligible Passengers Per Bus

Now count how many passengers are eligible for each bus.

SELECT
    bus_id,
    capacity,
    COUNT(passenger_id) AS eligible_passengers
FROM cte
GROUP BY bus_id, capacity;
Example
rank	bus_id	capacity	eligible_passengers
1	1	1	2
2	2	10	2
3	3	2	5
Step 3 — Actual Boarding Logic

Now we must determine how many passengers actually board each bus.

For every bus:

onboarded=min(capacity,eligible_remaining)

But:

eligible_remaining=current_eligible−previously_onboarded

So we must continuously track:

Total eligible passengers
Total passengers already onboarded

This is why a recursive CTE is useful.

Recursive CTE Thinking

For each bus:

First Bus
eligible = current eligible passengers
onboarded = MIN(capacity, eligible)
Example
capacity	eligible	onboarded
1	2	1
Second Bus

Remaining eligible passengers:

current eligible−total onboarded so far

Then:

onboarded=min(capacity,remaining eligible)
Important Observation

Passengers board buses in arrival order.

So:

Earlier buses consume passengers first.
Future buses only get the remaining passengers.
Edge Cases
1. Use LEFT JOIN

We should use LEFT JOIN while counting because some buses may have:

0 eligible passengers

and we still want those buses in the result.

2. Use COUNT(passenger_id)

Use:

COUNT(passenger_id)

NOT:

COUNT(*)
Reason

With LEFT JOIN, unmatched rows produce NULL.

COUNT(*) would incorrectly count them.

Recursive CTE State Tracking

Inside the recursive CTE, keep track of:

Column	Meaning
onboarded	Passengers boarded in current bus
total_so_far	Total passengers boarded till current bus

Then for the next bus:

remaining_eligible=current_eligible−total_so_far

and again:

onboarded=min(capacity,remaining_eligible)
